It appears that the {{count}} function does not respect the read preference.

Documentation: [http://mongodb.github.io/node-mongodb-native/3.1/api/Cursor.html#count]

I have not tried to give the options to the {{find}} function, but {{setReadPreference}} works.

Passing the query string {{'?foo=bar&foo=baz'}} results in the options object

{ foo: 'bar' }

but it should result in

{ foo: [ 'bar', 'baz' ] }

This is because of [this line in the uri parser|https://github.com/mongodb-js/mongodb-core/blob/c93aac13149745845bce2be23c7268bde7e14faf/lib/uri_parser.js#L140] where the variable name {{value}} is being used both as the array to filter on as well as an argument to the callback function within filter itself.

h2. Description

In https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/core/document/ I saw that *"The field names cannot contain the dot (.) character."* but I have managed to {color:red}insert broken documents{color} using the default code options of the {color:red}nodejs 3.0.6 driver{color}.

h2. Steps to reproduce

- Install the environment : 
1. mongodb 3.2.18, node v8.11.1, npm 5.6.0, ubuntu 12.04
2. *package.json*
{code}
"dependencies": {
    "mongodb": "^3.0.6",
}
{code}

- Run the following *index.js* file:
{code}
const {MongoClient} = require('mongodb');

const uri = 'mongodb://localhost:27017/admin';

(async () => {

    const client = await MongoClient.connect(uri);
    const db = client.db('test');

    let records = [{
        "a.b.c": 1
    }, {
        "d.e": 1
    }
    ];

    await db.collection("sample").insertMany(records);

    let dbRecords = await db.collection("sample").find({}).toArray();
    console.log(dbRecords);

})();
{code}

